{{Short description|U.S. military program to develop small arms}}
[[File:Next Generation Squad Weapon Program.png|thumb|upright=1.35|A U.S. Army graphic detailing the competitors for the program as of December 2020.]]

The '''Next Generation Squad Weapon''' ('''NGSW''') program is a [[United States Armed Forces|United States military]] program created in 2017 by the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] to replace the [[5.56×45mm NATO|5.56mm]] [[M4 carbine]], the [[M249 SAW]] light machine gun, and the 7.62mm [[M240 machine gun]], with a common system of 6.8mm cartridges and to develop small arms [[Fire-control system|fire-control systems]] for the new weapons.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |date=12 July 2018 |title=Army is saying goodbye to the M249 Squad Automatic Rifle after thirty years |url=https://popularmilitary.com/army-saying-goodbye-m249-squad-automatic-rifle-thirty-years/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231005121519/https://popularmilitary.com/army-saying-goodbye-m249-squad-automatic-rifle-thirty-years/ |archive-date=5 October 2023 |access-date=20 August 2021 |website=Popular Military}}</ref><ref name=":3" />

Seven defense manufacturers competed in the program, with five attempting to design and produce the weapons and two attempting to create and supply fire-control optics.<ref name="tfb fcs contract">{{Cite web |last=Moss |first=Matthew |date=7 January 2022 |title=Vortex Win US Army Next Generation Squad Weapons - Fire Control Contract - |url=https://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2022/01/07/vortex-win-us-army-next-generation-squad-weapons-fire-control-contract/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220603013530/https://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2022/01/07/vortex-win-us-army-next-generation-squad-weapons-fire-control-contract/ |archive-date=3 June 2022 |website=The Firearm Blog}}</ref> The winners were officially announced by the Army in early 2022: [[SIG Sauer]] to produce the [[XM7]] rifle and [[XM250]] automatic rifle, [[Vortex Optics]] to produce the XM157 fire-control system,<ref name="tfb fcs contract" /> and [[Olin Corporation|Winchester]] to produce the custom [[6.8×51mm Common Cartridge]] ammunition designed by SIG Sauer.<ref name=":42">{{Cite web |author= |date=19 April 2022 |title=Army awards Next Generation Squad Weapon contract |url=https://www.army.mil/article/255827/army_awards_next_generation_squad_weapon_contract |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220420013414/https://www.army.mil/article/255827/army_awards_next_generation_squad_weapon_contract |archive-date=20 April 2022 |access-date=19 April 2022 |website=U.S. Army}}</ref><ref name=":02">{{Cite web |last=Cox |first=Matthew |date=20 December 2018 |title=Army to Seek Prototypes for M4/M249 SAW Replacements in Early 2019 |url=https://www.military.com/kitup/2018/12/20/army-seek-prototypes-m4-m249-saw-replacements-early-2019.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220315145136/https://www.military.com/kitup/2018/12/20/army-seek-prototypes-m4-m249-saw-replacements-early-2019.html |archive-date=15 March 2022 |access-date=20 August 2021 |website=Military.com |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":12">{{Cite web |last=Woody |first=Christopher |date=12 June 2017 |title=The Army wants to ditch the M249 SAW and give the infantry more firepower |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/army-looking-for-replacement-for-m249-squad-automatic-weapon-2017-6 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220525075356/https://www.businessinsider.com/army-looking-for-replacement-for-m249-squad-automatic-weapon-2017-6 |archive-date=25 May 2022 |access-date=20 August 2021 |website=Business Insider |language=en-US}}</ref> The program was expected to cost $10 million in the first year of production, and $150 million the next.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":02" /><ref name=":12" />

== History ==
The NGSW program began in 2017, after the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] issued an order for the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] to conduct an assessment regarding the need to upgrade existing [[M4 carbine]]s with [[United States Special Operations Command|SOCOM]]'s [[SOPMOD]] free-floating [[Rail Integration System|rail]]. It was concluded that the M4 carbine was still favored by troops and also performed well under stress. Feeding issues and other problems were fixed by using different ammunition types and magazines. Despite this, the M4 had difficulty penetrating the types of [[bulletproof vest]]s used by [[List of equipment of the Russian Ground Forces|Russian]] and [[List of equipment of the People's Liberation Army Ground Force|Chinese]] troops, especially at longer ranges.{{fact|date=May 2022}} Pressure to develop a new weapon system also arose from military programs created by other countries, such as Russia's [[Ratnik (program)|Ratnik program]].{{fact|date=May 2022}} The U.S. Army's Soldier Enhancement Program released its findings in December 2017, which recommended proceeding with the Next Generation Squad Weapon Program as a more cost-effective solution compared to only retrofitting M4s with free-float rail systems.<ref name="congress ngsw">{{cite web |date=5 June 2018 |title=S. Rept. 115-262 - The John S. McCain National Defense Authorization Act For Fiscal Year 2019 |url=https://www.congress.gov/congressional-report/115th-congress/senate-report/262 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915235940/https://www.congress.gov/congressional-report/115th-congress/senate-report/262 |archive-date=15 September 2019 |access-date=3 June 2022 |website=Congress.gov |publisher=Library of Congress}}</ref>

Previous attempts to replace the M4 failed due to lack of funding, poor submissions, or re-evaluation of tactics and requirements.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Winward |first=Tim |date=27 May 2000 |title=Objective Infantry Combat Weapon |url=http://216.117.156.23/features/tangofox/2000/february/oicw.shtml |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210307220940/https://web.archive.org/web/20000527170738/http://216.117.156.23/features/tangofox/2000/february/oicw.shtml |archive-date=7 March 2021 |access-date=21 April 2022 |website=Tango Fox}}</ref>{{Reliable source|date=June 2022}}<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cox |first=Matthew |date=October 2017 |title=Army: Gun Makers Didn't Meet Reliability Standard |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2013/06/14/army-gun-makers-didnt-meet-reliability-standard.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618063923/https://www.military.com/daily-news/2013/06/14/army-gun-makers-didnt-meet-reliability-standard.html |archive-date=18 June 2013 |access-date=21 April 2022 |website=Military.com |language=en}}</ref> These included the [[Objective Individual Combat Weapon]] program, the [[Special Purpose Individual Weapon]] program, and the [[Advanced Combat Rifle]] program ''(not to be confused with the [[Remington ACR|Adaptive Combat Rifle]])''.

== Program components ==

=== Weapons ===
[[File:SIG Sauer XM5.png|thumb|The SIG M7, the winning assault rifle submission for the NGSW program]]
[[File:XM250 automatic rifle.jpg|thumb|SIG M250, the winning automatic rifle with inserted ammunition belt]]

In 2017, the U.S. Army issued requirements for prototype Next Generation Squad Weapon submissions.<ref name=":2"/><ref name=":3">{{Cite web |title=Next Generation Squad Weapons (NGSW) |url=https://asc.army.mil/web/portfolio-item/fws-cs-2/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240113074709/https://asc.army.mil/web/portfolio-item/fws-cs-2/ |archive-date=13 January 2024 |access-date=7 October 2021 |website=U.S. Army Acquisition Support Center |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":12" /> The program's rifle requirement, referred to as NGSW-R, was required to use a 6.8mm round and be able to utilize small arms fire-control systems. The program's support weapon, referred to as NGSW-AR, was required to be no longer than {{convert|35|in|abbr=on}}; no heavier than {{convert|12|lb|abbr=on}} including attachments; able to suppress targets out to {{convert|3,900|ft|m|abbr=on}}; able to accurately fire on targets out to {{convert|2,000|ft|m|abbr=on}}; able to make use of small arms [[fire-control system]]s.

On April 19, 2022, after 27 months of prototyping and evaluation, the Army announced that [[SIG Sauer]] was awarded the NGSW program contract, and would produce the replacements for the M4 carbine and M249 SAW for the next 10 years.<ref name="defense daily">{{Cite web |last=Beinart |first=Matthew |date=19 April 2022 |title=Sig Sauer Wins 10-Year Deal To Deliver Army's Next-Gen Squad Weapons |url=https://www.defensedaily.com/sig-sauer-wins-10-year-deal-to-deliver-armys-next-gen-squad-weapons/army/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220419221747/https://www.defensedaily.com/sig-sauer-wins-10-year-deal-to-deliver-armys-next-gen-squad-weapons/army/ |archive-date=19 April 2022 |access-date=25 April 2022 |website=Defense Daily |language=en-US}}</ref> The new rifle, designated the [[XM7]], is based on the company's [[SIG MCX Spear]] rifle, while the new automatic rifle, designated the [[XM250]], is based on the company's SIG MG 6.8mm belt-fed gun.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Beynon |first=Steve |date=19 April 2022 |title=Army Picks Its Replacement for the M4 and SAW |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2022/04/19/army-picks-its-replacement-m4-and-saw.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220520175414/https://www.military.com/daily-news/2022/04/19/army-picks-its-replacement-m4-and-saw.html |archive-date=20 May 2022 |access-date=2 June 2022 |website=Military.com |language=en-US}}</ref>

The company was awarded a small initial production order, worth $10.4 million, for about 25 rifles, 15 automatic rifles, and a “large quantity” of ammunition so the weapons could be tested and the production line fine-tuned.<ref name="defense one">{{Cite web |last=Kenney |first=Caitlyn M. |date=20 April 2022 |title=Soldiers Will Have to Wait Until Next Year for New Rifle, Ammo |url=https://www.defenseone.com/business/2022/04/soldiers-will-have-wait-until-next-year-new-rifle-ammo/365906/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220518041807/https://www.defenseone.com/business/2022/04/soldiers-will-have-wait-until-next-year-new-rifle-ammo/365906/ |archive-date=18 May 2022 |access-date=22 April 2022 |website=Defense One |language=en}}</ref>

A [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] press release stated the new weapons would "provide significant capability improvements in accuracy, range and overall lethality. They are lightweight, fire more lethal ammunition, mitigate recoil, provide improved barrel performance, and include integrated muzzle sound and flash reduction."<ref name=":42"/>

The U.S. Army intends to procure 111,428 M7 Rifles, 13,334 M250 Machine Guns, and 124,749 Fire Control systems through the life of the program.<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 2023 |title=Justification Book Volume 1 of 1 Procurement of W&TCV, Army |url=https://www.asafm.army.mil/Portals/72/Documents/BudgetMaterial/2024/Base%20Budget/Procurement/Procurement%20of%20Weapons%20and%20Tracked%20Combat%20Vehicles.pdf }}</ref>

