=== Fire-control systems ===
[[File:Enhanced Night Vision Goggles Technical Demonstration Image 5 of 36 6149249 190411-A-HE309-005.jpg|thumb|Vortex Optics XM157 platform agnostic fire-control system]]

The program also included the development of new [[Fire-control system|fire-control systems]] for small-arms weapons. Two companies entered the competition: Vortex Optics and [[L3Harris Technologies]], both of whose submissions utilized integrated fire-control systems using [[laser rangefinder]]s, direct view optics, digital overlays, and [[external ballistics|ballistic calculation systems]], as per NGSW program requirements.<ref name=":0" /> In late January 2022, the U.S. Army selected [[Vortex Optics]]' offering, designated the '''XM157''' fire-control system.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Keller |first=Jared |date=2 February 2021 |title=This could be the Army's next-generation rifle optic of choice |url=https://taskandpurpose.com/military-tech/army-next-generation-squad-weapon-fire-control-l3harris/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220605234723/https://taskandpurpose.com/military-tech/army-next-generation-squad-weapon-fire-control-l3harris/ |archive-date=5 June 2022 |access-date=6 October 2021 |website=Task & Purpose |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Edwards |first=Jane |date=10 January 2022 |title=Vortex Optics to Produce Next-Gen Fire Controls Under $2.7B Army Follow-On OTA |url=https://www.govconwire.com/2022/01/vortex-optics-to-produce-next-gen-fire-controls-under-2-7b-army-follow-on-ota/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220216063545/https://www.govconwire.com/2022/01/vortex-optics-to-produce-next-gen-fire-controls-under-2-7b-army-follow-on-ota/ |archive-date=16 February 2022 |website=GovConWire}}</ref>

=== Ammunition ===
NGSW weapon proposals used proponent designed cartridges with government-issued 6.8mm general-purpose projectiles. This allowed each proposed weapon and cartridge to be designed together to meet the performance requirements. In January 2022, Winchester was awarded a contract to produce the ammunition. In April 2022, with the selection of the MCX Spear, SIG Sauer's hybrid metal cartridge would become the new cartridge subsequently referred to as [[.277 Fury|6.8x51mm Common Cartridge]] by the U.S. Army.<ref name=":42"/>

